Belore l pass to other matters l should like to say a few words on the author os the Memoranda. He gives no hint as to who he was, but itis obvious that he must have been at least a canon ol the House, and probably one who held some high office, lor in no other way could he have had access to the documents and private, matters with which he deals. Itis probable that he based his work on that of a previous historian; lor, when he is telling the story ol Prior Domesman's generosity in giving his father's land to the House (p. 98), he says: “so wrote Canon Guarinus,'’ but he evidently has doubts about his accuracy, lor he adds: “I do not remember to have seen the deod ol gist.'' That he examined originals is obvious from the way in which he notes minute particulars—as the colour ol the wax ol which a Royal Seal was made, and its condition. lle may have been a student in the neighbouring University, sor he was evidently a learned person, who wrote a good style, and was well acquainted with classical Latin. Whoever he was, the epithets which

he applies to Prior Gerard (p. 64), when he calls him pleasant, and very good humoured omnm et hyllan's valde), might have been applied with justice to himself. There is, ol course, what l may call a professional tone about a good deal os his narrative ; the world is very evil ; the monastic orders arethe objects ol a cruel persecution; the hand ol' every man is against them3 and almost any

weapon may justiliably be used by them to combat their enemies.
